WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.030 --> 00:00:04.514
Prof: What we're doing
this week is extending our

00:00:04.514 --> 00:00:08.252
conversation we started last
week about how was Paul used as

00:00:08.252 --> 00:00:10.470
a figure in early Christianity.
 

00:00:10.470 --> 00:00:13.500
Today we're going to talk about
the Pastoral Epistles,

00:00:13.500 --> 00:00:15.920
which is I and II Timothy and
Titus,

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:19.227
and then next time we'll talk
about The Acts of Paul and

00:00:19.227 --> 00:00:22.649
Thecla because these are two
practically opposite ways of

00:00:22.649 --> 00:00:26.242
interpreting Paul and using Paul
that came about probably in the

00:00:26.242 --> 00:00:27.440
second century.
 

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:31.808
The Pastoral Epistles are
called "pastoral"

00:00:31.808 --> 00:00:36.850
because it presents Paul as
writing to Timothy and Titus,

00:00:36.850 --> 00:00:40.081
two of his followers,
but he's telling them how to be

00:00:40.081 --> 00:00:41.760
good pastors of a church.
 

00:00:41.760 --> 00:00:45.551
In fact he's also doing
something like almost acting

00:00:45.551 --> 00:00:48.450
like they're going to become
bishops;

00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:51.789
they are also supposed to be
appointing other people as

00:00:51.789 --> 00:00:53.150
pastors of churches.
 

00:00:53.150 --> 00:00:56.632
We call these the Pastoral
Epistles because it presents

00:00:56.632 --> 00:01:00.307
Paul as himself serving in a
sort of pastoral role for his

00:01:00.307 --> 00:01:04.305
churches and assigning Timothy
and Titus pastoral roles for his

00:01:04.305 --> 00:01:07.030
churches also,
and establishing leadership

00:01:07.030 --> 00:01:08.816
positions,
what kind of leadership

00:01:08.816 --> 00:01:11.170
structures he wants to go on in
the churches.

00:01:11.170 --> 00:01:14.462
Most of us scholars believe
that these letters are

00:01:14.462 --> 00:01:15.468
pseudonymous.
 

00:01:15.468 --> 00:01:17.010
We don't believe Paul wrote
them.

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:20.724
There has been some question in
the last several years that

00:01:20.724 --> 00:01:24.504
maybe the actual historical Paul
wrote II Timothy because II

00:01:24.504 --> 00:01:28.283
Timothy looks sort of like a
last will and testament of Paul

00:01:28.283 --> 00:01:30.909
that he may have written in
prison.

00:01:30.909 --> 00:01:33.750
But I don't tend to buy that.
 

00:01:33.750 --> 00:01:36.402
I tend to group all three of
them together as being probably

00:01:36.402 --> 00:01:38.560
by the same author and all being
pseudonymous.

00:01:38.560 --> 00:01:40.440
Why do we think they're
pseudonymous?

00:01:40.440 --> 00:01:43.590
Well again, as we saw with
Ephesians and Colossians,

00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:47.042
the writing style in these
letters is very different from

00:01:47.042 --> 00:01:51.050
the seven letters that scholars
all agree Paul actually wrote,

00:01:51.050 --> 00:01:52.640
so the writing style is a big
issue.

00:01:52.640 --> 00:01:56.402
As I'll show today there are a
lot of ways of seeing that these

00:01:56.402 --> 00:01:59.498
letters simply presuppose a
different stage in early

00:01:59.498 --> 00:02:00.530
Christianity.
 

00:02:00.530 --> 00:02:04.230
They don't look like they're
from the more primitive sort of

00:02:04.230 --> 00:02:07.430
time of when Paul was actually
founding churches.

00:02:07.430 --> 00:02:11.117
The theology looks different,
the church structure looks

00:02:11.117 --> 00:02:13.140
different,
as I'll talk about,

00:02:13.140 --> 00:02:15.592
positions on the household,
on marriage,

00:02:15.592 --> 00:02:18.937
on slavery, on family,
on women, all of these things

00:02:18.937 --> 00:02:19.949
are different.
 

00:02:19.949 --> 00:02:24.254
I'm using the Pastoral Epistles
in this lecture as one

00:02:24.254 --> 00:02:28.479
illustration of how Christianity
changes in different

00:02:28.479 --> 00:02:29.860
trajectories.
 

00:02:29.860 --> 00:02:33.878
One trajectory becomes very
much pro-household.

00:02:33.878 --> 00:02:38.330
The traditional Roman style or
Greco-Roman family is promoted

00:02:38.330 --> 00:02:42.115
as the Christian way for
families to be and even the

00:02:42.115 --> 00:02:46.122
church itself is molded to look
like a household with a

00:02:46.122 --> 00:02:49.776
paterfamilias,
the head of the household on

00:02:49.776 --> 00:02:52.979
top, women below that,
children and slaves below that.

00:02:52.979 --> 00:02:56.210
When we get to The Acts of
Paul and Thecla, we'll see

00:02:56.210 --> 00:02:59.550
that that interpretation of Paul
makes Paul anti-household.

00:02:59.550 --> 00:03:02.622
He actually is presented as
going around preaching against

00:03:02.622 --> 00:03:03.947
marriage,
against sex,

00:03:03.947 --> 00:03:07.548
against the Roman household,
and preaching a very kind of

00:03:07.548 --> 00:03:10.075
hierarchical disrupting,
even city-,

00:03:10.075 --> 00:03:14.204
polis-disrupting Gospel
and certainly a household- and

00:03:14.204 --> 00:03:16.199
family-disrupting Apostle.
 

00:03:16.199 --> 00:03:20.258
These two trajectories of
Pauline Christianity show the

00:03:20.258 --> 00:03:23.639
diversity of Christianity as it
developed,

00:03:23.639 --> 00:03:25.800
and even how they used the same
figure,

00:03:25.800 --> 00:03:29.168
Paul, as founder of
Christianity in radically

00:03:29.168 --> 00:03:30.470
different ways.
 

00:03:30.470 --> 00:03:33.020
When did these letters come
about?

00:03:33.020 --> 00:03:34.940
It's everybody guess.
 

00:03:34.940 --> 00:03:37.818
I actually tend to think that
the Pastoral Epistles were

00:03:37.818 --> 00:03:40.490
probably written sometime in the
second century,

00:03:40.490 --> 00:03:43.610
and maybe even toward the
middle of the second century.

00:03:43.610 --> 00:03:46.888
That's a bit later than a lot
of scholars would put them,

00:03:46.888 --> 00:03:48.818
and we're just guessing anyway.
 

00:03:48.818 --> 00:03:51.645
We sort of have to imagine what
kind of level of early

00:03:51.645 --> 00:03:53.992
Christianity,
what kind of phase of early

00:03:53.992 --> 00:03:57.090
Christianity do we imagine
taking place before we can get

00:03:57.090 --> 00:04:00.296
this kind of a letter with this
kind of theology and church

00:04:00.296 --> 00:04:01.568
structure written.
 

00:04:01.568 --> 00:04:05.413
It is interesting that when we
talked about Marcion early,

00:04:05.413 --> 00:04:09.191
remember the heretic in Rome
who made his own first Canon

00:04:09.191 --> 00:04:11.348
list of New Testament books?
 

00:04:11.348 --> 00:04:14.144
Remember he included Luke as
his Gospel in his own edited

00:04:14.144 --> 00:04:16.740
version of it and he included
the letters of Paul.

00:04:16.740 --> 00:04:20.112
We don't have any evidence that
Marcion actually knew about

00:04:20.112 --> 00:04:23.019
these three letters,
I and II Timothy and Titus.

00:04:23.019 --> 00:04:26.720
If Marcion was writing in the
middle of the second century,

00:04:26.720 --> 00:04:29.339
maybe Marcion,
if he didn't mention them,

00:04:29.339 --> 00:04:31.516
maybe he didn't know them,
and maybe that's evidence that

00:04:31.516 --> 00:04:33.615
they weren't yet highly
circulated so that's one of the

00:04:33.615 --> 00:04:35.250
things that people have talked
about,

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:36.829
the dating of these letters.
 

00:04:36.829 --> 00:04:39.644
Since Marcion didn't seem to
know them, perhaps they were

00:04:39.644 --> 00:04:42.762
either just being written or not
long written around the middle

00:04:42.762 --> 00:04:44.069
of the second century.
 

00:04:44.069 --> 00:04:49.716
First let me back up because I
want to go through Paul really

00:04:49.716 --> 00:04:55.271
quickly and talk about what
Paul's own view of the household

00:04:55.271 --> 00:04:55.930
is.
 

00:04:55.930 --> 00:04:58.718
Look with me in 1 Corinthians
7, we're going to review some

00:04:58.718 --> 00:05:01.795
things that we've gone on before
but keep your Bibles in front of

00:05:01.795 --> 00:05:02.180
you.
 

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:12.771
Look at 1 Corinthians 7:1:
Concerning the matters about

00:05:12.771 --> 00:05:14.649
which you wrote,
"it is well for a man not

00:05:14.649 --> 00:05:15.709
to touch a woman."
 

00:05:15.709 --> 00:05:18.884
But because of cases of sexual
immorality each man should have

00:05:18.884 --> 00:05:21.278
his own wife and each woman her
own husband;

00:05:21.278 --> 00:05:23.790
the husband should give his
wife her conjugal rights,

00:05:23.790 --> 00:05:25.480
likewise the wife to her
husband.

00:05:25.480 --> 00:05:27.629
Notice how Paul balances these
things.

00:05:27.629 --> 00:05:30.204
He tells basically the man,
you have control of the body of

00:05:30.204 --> 00:05:32.911
your wife, but he also tells to
the woman, you have control of

00:05:32.911 --> 00:05:34.199
the body of your husband.
 

00:05:34.199 --> 00:05:38.649
There's something of
reciprocity in 1 Corinthians 7.

00:05:38.649 --> 00:05:42.065
This will be important because
that kind of reciprocity doesn't

00:05:42.065 --> 00:05:44.600
exist when you get to the
Pastoral Epistles.

00:05:44.600 --> 00:05:47.100
That's one thing to notice.
 

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:50.252
Verse 5:
Do not deprive one another

00:05:50.252 --> 00:05:52.812
except perhaps by agreement for
a set time to devote yourselves

00:05:52.812 --> 00:05:53.350
to prayer.
 

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:55.538
Then come together again so
that Satan may not tempt you

00:05:55.538 --> 00:05:57.089
because of your lack of self
control.

00:05:57.089 --> 00:05:59.740
This I say by way of
concession, not of command.

00:05:59.740 --> 00:06:02.165
I wish that all were as I
myself am but each has a

00:06:02.165 --> 00:06:04.939
particular gift from God,
one having one kind and another

00:06:04.939 --> 00:06:05.980
a different kind.
 

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:09.639
Notice he's basically saying,
have sex within marriage.

00:06:09.639 --> 00:06:13.666
He's not condemning sex,
but he really prefers that all

00:06:13.666 --> 00:06:16.800
Christians be single like he
himself is.

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:19.668
Paul's preference is not
marriage and sex within

00:06:19.668 --> 00:06:20.339
marriage.
 

00:06:20.339 --> 00:06:23.423
That's a concession that he
gives for people that he says

00:06:23.423 --> 00:06:24.910
can't control themselves.
 

00:06:24.910 --> 00:06:28.793
To the unmarried and widows,
I say that it is well for them

00:06:28.793 --> 00:06:32.127
to remain unmarried as I am,
but if they are not practicing

00:06:32.127 --> 00:06:33.470
self control they should marry.
 

00:06:33.470 --> 00:06:36.029
It is better to marry than to
burn.

00:06:36.029 --> 00:06:38.180
That's what the Greek actually
says, "It is better to

00:06:38.180 --> 00:06:39.199
marry than to burn."
 

00:06:39.199 --> 00:06:41.134
That's been an interesting
question of scholars,

00:06:41.134 --> 00:06:42.779
what does he mean by
"burn"?

00:06:42.779 --> 00:06:44.050
Does he mean burn in hell?
 

00:06:44.050 --> 00:06:46.588
That it's better to marry than
to be tempted to sin with sex

00:06:46.588 --> 00:06:48.740
outside of marriage and then
you'd burn in hell?

00:06:48.740 --> 00:06:52.120
I've argued that what he means
is "burn with desire"

00:06:52.120 --> 00:06:55.500
because it was very common in
ancient Greek culture to portray

00:06:55.500 --> 00:06:58.879
any kind of erotic desire as
actually a physical burning.

00:06:58.879 --> 00:07:00.560
They even portrayed it as a
disease.

00:07:00.560 --> 00:07:03.810
When you start having that
itchy feeling that we all know

00:07:03.810 --> 00:07:05.959
so well,
that's because your body is

00:07:05.959 --> 00:07:09.512
actually heating up,
and that's what causes that

00:07:09.512 --> 00:07:10.199
desire.
 

00:07:10.199 --> 00:07:13.870
The ancient Greek doctors,
Greek and Roman doctors,

00:07:13.870 --> 00:07:16.656
gave all kinds of prescriptions
to people to control that

00:07:16.656 --> 00:07:19.591
burning so they can control
their erotic desire because they

00:07:19.591 --> 00:07:21.829
felt like it made you actually
unhealthy.

00:07:21.829 --> 00:07:25.810
Desire was unhealthy and sexual
activity was dangerous.

00:07:25.810 --> 00:07:28.273
This was a concern throughout
the ancient world and I think

00:07:28.273 --> 00:07:29.759
that's what Paul's talking
about.

00:07:29.759 --> 00:07:32.048
What I've argued,
and have argued this in my

00:07:32.048 --> 00:07:34.550
Corinthian body book and a few
other places,

00:07:34.550 --> 00:07:39.449
is that Paul actually prefers
that people avoid sex entirely,

00:07:39.449 --> 00:07:40.740
Christians avoid sex entirely.
 

00:07:40.740 --> 00:07:42.863
If they can't avoid sex
entirely, and they're starting

00:07:42.863 --> 00:07:45.470
to have sexual desire burning in
them and that gets dangerous,

00:07:45.470 --> 00:07:49.004
then they should get married
and have sex but only to

00:07:49.004 --> 00:07:50.569
decrease the burning.
 

00:07:50.569 --> 00:07:54.322
What Paul wants is for them to
experience sexual intercourse,

00:07:54.322 --> 00:07:57.199
even in marriage,
without any erotic desire.

00:07:57.199 --> 00:08:00.185
Now that's kind of a radical
idea but I believe that's

00:08:00.185 --> 00:08:02.439
actually what Paul was teaching
here,

00:08:02.439 --> 00:08:05.874
is that he concedes it possible
that Christians could have sex

00:08:05.874 --> 00:08:09.250
without experiencing desire,
and that's his goal.

00:08:09.250 --> 00:08:12.735
Notice Paul doesn't have a very
positive view of sex,

00:08:12.735 --> 00:08:15.951
even within marriage,
it's a concession he allows

00:08:15.951 --> 00:08:16.689
people.
 

00:08:16.689 --> 00:08:20.122
Notice in none of this passage
does he talk at all about having

00:08:20.122 --> 00:08:20.509
kids.
 

00:08:20.509 --> 00:08:24.884
Sexuality for Paul is not to
make children in Paul's own

00:08:24.884 --> 00:08:25.680
letters.
 

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:29.379
You have sex in marriage only
to keep you from desiring.

00:08:29.379 --> 00:08:31.129
That's Paul's concern.
 

00:08:31.129 --> 00:08:34.029
That will change later.
 

00:08:34.029 --> 00:08:36.907
That's one place where--we also
saw in I Thessalonians 4,

00:08:36.907 --> 00:08:39.629
if you'll remember,
we had this same kind of thing.

00:08:39.629 --> 00:08:43.500
There, Paul is just talking to
the men of the congregation and

00:08:43.500 --> 00:08:46.990
he says, don't you start wanting
your brother's wife.

00:08:46.990 --> 00:08:49.224
He calls them skeuos,
your vessel,

00:08:49.224 --> 00:08:52.519
he says, "Each of you
should have your vessel."

00:08:52.519 --> 00:08:56.250
And the debate is whether he's
talking about their genitalia,

00:08:56.250 --> 00:08:58.070
which is one possible
interpretation of the Greek,

00:08:58.070 --> 00:09:00.200
or their wife's body,
which is another possible

00:09:00.200 --> 00:09:01.590
interpretation of the Greek.
 

00:09:01.590 --> 00:09:05.928
For Paul, in I Thessalonians 4,
he's telling men also,

00:09:05.928 --> 00:09:08.923
control yourself--and he says,
"Not in passion of desire

00:09:08.923 --> 00:09:11.070
like the Gentiles,"
so there again,

00:09:11.070 --> 00:09:14.690
in I Thessalonians,
4, Paul is really concerned

00:09:14.690 --> 00:09:19.255
that the Thessalonian disciples
are not lusting after their

00:09:19.255 --> 00:09:21.460
fellow Christian's wife.
 

00:09:21.460 --> 00:09:25.461
Keep your own vessel,
and that's how your control

00:09:25.461 --> 00:09:26.379
yourself.
 

00:09:26.379 --> 00:09:29.610
And notice again he's excluding
the idea of passion and desire.

00:09:29.610 --> 00:09:31.720
It just does not have a part in
it.

00:09:31.720 --> 00:09:35.009
I admit that this is kind of a
radical argument,

00:09:35.009 --> 00:09:37.226
and there are a lot of people
out there who haven't bought my

00:09:37.226 --> 00:09:38.859
argument,
but that seems to me to be

00:09:38.859 --> 00:09:40.460
precisely what the text is
saying.

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:45.624
Paul never allows for a good
notion of sexual pleasure or

00:09:45.624 --> 00:09:47.100
sexual desire.
 

00:09:47.100 --> 00:09:50.216
He seems to want to exclude it
in order to keep you from

00:09:50.216 --> 00:09:53.275
experiencing desire and he
believes that he can do that

00:09:53.275 --> 00:09:54.580
even by having sex.
 

00:09:54.580 --> 00:09:58.418
In those ways we see Paul is
not anti-marriage exactly,

00:09:58.418 --> 00:10:00.019
but he's certainly not
pro-marriage,

00:10:00.019 --> 00:10:04.528
and he's not anti-sex exactly,
but he's certainly is not

00:10:04.528 --> 00:10:05.350
pro-sex.
 

00:10:05.350 --> 00:10:09.265
The one thing he does seem to
be anti is desire,

00:10:09.265 --> 00:10:10.600
sexual desire.
 

00:10:10.600 --> 00:10:13.340
All right, where do women fit
in all this?

00:10:13.340 --> 00:10:16.710
I pointed out that in I
Thessalonians 4 Paul doesn't

00:10:16.710 --> 00:10:19.418
seem to think about women at all
there.

00:10:19.418 --> 00:10:22.400
In fact, I even proposed when I
lectured on I Thessalonians that

00:10:22.400 --> 00:10:24.200
by the time Paul wrote that
letter,

00:10:24.200 --> 00:10:25.600
which is one of his earliest
letters,

00:10:25.600 --> 00:10:27.370
maybe the earliest letter we
have in the Canon,

00:10:27.370 --> 00:10:30.501
Paul may have been conceiving
of the Christian group as being

00:10:30.501 --> 00:10:33.424
sort of a male club because
that's the way he tends to be

00:10:33.424 --> 00:10:34.470
talking to them.
 

00:10:34.470 --> 00:10:37.538
A male club of mainly working
class manual laborers.

00:10:37.538 --> 00:10:40.471
That's changed by the time we
get to I Corinthians,

00:10:40.471 --> 00:10:40.940
right?
 

00:10:40.940 --> 00:10:43.678
Because Paul directly talks
about women a lot,

00:10:43.678 --> 00:10:46.950
he sees women as being in
something like a co-relationship

00:10:46.950 --> 00:10:50.450
with their husbands and sexual
activity in I Corinthians 7.

00:10:50.450 --> 00:10:54.418
He addresses women as leaders
of churches at times.

00:10:54.418 --> 00:11:00.360
So by the time Paul writes I
Corinthians, women are

00:11:00.360 --> 00:11:06.538
acknowledged as an important
part of his churches.

00:11:06.538 --> 00:11:11.804
But in 1 Corinthians 11,
look there, he doesn't have

00:11:11.804 --> 00:11:17.690
women on a completely equal
stance with men apparently.

00:11:17.690 --> 00:11:21.211
In I Corinthians 11 he says:
I commend you because you

00:11:21.211 --> 00:11:23.666
remember me in everything and
maintain the traditions just as

00:11:23.666 --> 00:11:24.730
I handed them onto you.
 

00:11:24.730 --> 00:11:27.886
But I want you to understand
that Christ is the head of every

00:11:27.886 --> 00:11:31.150
man and the husband is ahead of
the wife as God is ahead of the

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:31.730
church.
 

00:11:31.730 --> 00:11:34.186
There is a clear hierarchy
there, and Paul goes on to talk

00:11:34.186 --> 00:11:36.859
about what this is going to have
to do with women veiling their

00:11:36.859 --> 00:11:38.538
heads when they pray and
prophesy,

00:11:38.538 --> 00:11:44.777
which another very complicated
and controversial passage in

00:11:44.777 --> 00:11:45.529
Paul.
 

00:11:45.529 --> 00:11:49.129
It's clear that Paul views,
just as he views God as the

00:11:49.129 --> 00:11:51.514
head of Christ,
that is Christ of being

00:11:51.514 --> 00:11:54.298
somewhat inferior person
compared to God the Father,

00:11:54.298 --> 00:11:57.884
so women are in an inferior
position with regard to their

00:11:57.884 --> 00:11:58.590
husbands.
 

00:11:58.590 --> 00:12:01.690
The Greek words here,
they're just the words for

00:12:01.690 --> 00:12:04.330
"man"
and "woman."

00:12:04.330 --> 00:12:06.783
But since the Greek doesn't
have special terms for

00:12:06.783 --> 00:12:08.785
"husband"
and "wife,"

00:12:08.785 --> 00:12:11.639
when you see a Greek term like
this in this context,

00:12:11.639 --> 00:12:14.570
you have to make the decision:
are you going to translate this

00:12:14.570 --> 00:12:16.442
as "man"
or "woman,"

00:12:16.442 --> 00:12:19.374
