00:14:57.139 --> 00:15:00.451
how does that fit then with
this 1 Corinthians 14 passage

00:15:00.451 --> 00:15:04.059
where Paul seems to be saying
women should be silent in church

00:15:04.059 --> 00:15:06.730
and be subordinate,
ask your husband at home.

00:15:06.730 --> 00:15:10.226
Did any of you notice that
those verses I just read in 1

00:15:10.226 --> 00:15:13.471
Corinthians 14 are in some
translations in brackets,

00:15:13.471 --> 00:15:14.678
in parentheses?
 

00:15:14.678 --> 00:15:18.515
How many people have a
translation of 1 Corinthians

00:15:18.515 --> 00:15:22.274
14:34-36 that's in either
brackets or parentheses?

00:15:22.274 --> 00:15:23.808
Raise your hand.
 

00:15:23.808 --> 00:15:26.085
How many people have a
translation where they're not in

00:15:26.085 --> 00:15:27.558
brackets or parentheses,
anybody?

00:15:27.558 --> 00:15:30.168
Okay, so some of you don't have
them in brackets.

00:15:30.168 --> 00:15:33.047
That's showing you that these
editors are not sure whether

00:15:33.047 --> 00:15:35.470
that was actually part of the
original letter.

00:15:35.470 --> 00:15:37.080
There's a dispute here.
 

00:15:37.080 --> 00:15:38.870
If you looked at your footnotes
of your Bible,

00:15:38.870 --> 00:15:41.490
your footnotes might even say,
"some ancient

00:15:41.490 --> 00:15:44.004
authorities"
don't include this or include

00:15:44.004 --> 00:15:46.080
these verses in a different
place.

00:15:46.080 --> 00:15:49.221
This is the issue,
and we do have some Greek

00:15:49.221 --> 00:15:51.114
texts,
some Greek manuscripts that

00:15:51.114 --> 00:15:53.720
either don't have these verses
or have them in a different

00:15:53.720 --> 00:15:54.679
place in the text.
 

00:15:54.679 --> 00:15:56.519
Well how would that happen?
 

00:15:56.519 --> 00:16:01.980
Well, the idea goes that some
scribe,

00:16:01.980 --> 00:16:05.778
at some point,
was copying over I Corinthians

00:16:05.778 --> 00:16:10.783
14 and got to the point where
this is in the text and wrote

00:16:10.783 --> 00:16:14.033
out in the margin,
well wait a minute this is not

00:16:14.033 --> 00:16:16.390
right because of course the
scribes are living at a later

00:16:16.390 --> 00:16:18.960
time when women definitely were
in a more inferior position in

00:16:18.960 --> 00:16:19.548
churches.
 

00:16:19.548 --> 00:16:21.379
They couldn't be priests,
they couldn't be bishops and

00:16:21.379 --> 00:16:23.822
this sort of thing,
and that scribe writes in,

00:16:23.822 --> 00:16:26.380
well no,
of course, women can't do that,

00:16:26.380 --> 00:16:30.019
so there's a little note that
occurs there on the margins of

00:16:30.019 --> 00:16:30.759
the text.
 

00:16:30.759 --> 00:16:33.346
Other scribes come along and
find this manuscript and they

00:16:33.346 --> 00:16:35.889
decide, well that shouldn't be
out here in the margin;

00:16:35.889 --> 00:16:37.610
that should go into the text
someplace.

00:16:37.610 --> 00:16:41.203
So one scribe copying it over
puts that excerpt in this part

00:16:41.203 --> 00:16:44.980
of the text and another one puts
it in this part of the text in

00:16:44.980 --> 00:16:46.259
different places.
 

00:16:46.259 --> 00:16:49.220
And then those manuscripts are
copied over by other scribes.

00:16:49.220 --> 00:16:53.179
And you end up with Greek
manuscripts with these verses in

00:16:53.179 --> 00:16:55.889
different places in I
Corinthians 14.

00:16:55.889 --> 00:17:00.275
Some scholars have said that
all looks like those verses that

00:17:00.275 --> 00:17:04.663
teach the subordination of women
in I Corinthians 14 were not

00:17:04.663 --> 00:17:09.269
originally by Paul but were a
later scribal interpolation,

00:17:09.269 --> 00:17:11.788
insertion into the text.
 

00:17:11.788 --> 00:17:15.630
Other scholars disagree with
that, and they think that these

00:17:15.630 --> 00:17:18.558
verses were original with I
Corinthians 14.

00:17:18.558 --> 00:17:20.281
In other words,
I've given you a lot of

00:17:20.281 --> 00:17:21.368
problems to deal with.
 

00:17:21.368 --> 00:17:24.327
If you're going to talk about
what was Paul's view of women

00:17:24.327 --> 00:17:26.776
you've got to figure out,
well, what do you think

00:17:26.776 --> 00:17:28.509
Galatians 3:28 really teaches.
 

00:17:28.509 --> 00:17:30.700
Is it an egalitarian statement
or not?

00:17:30.700 --> 00:17:33.864
Is I Corinthians 14--these
verses--is that part of Paul's

00:17:33.864 --> 00:17:35.390
original teaching or not?
 

00:17:35.390 --> 00:17:38.836
Then you've got the situation
where in Romans 16,

00:17:38.836 --> 00:17:42.930
several verses in Romans 16,
Paul actually addresses women

00:17:42.930 --> 00:17:44.868
as leaders of churches.
 

00:17:44.868 --> 00:17:47.893
There are places where Paul is
willing to talk to women as

00:17:47.893 --> 00:17:49.058
leaders of churches.
 

00:17:49.058 --> 00:17:51.808
In fact, one of the verses in I
Corinthians 16,

00:17:51.808 --> 00:17:56.380
Paul addresses two people,
Andronicus and Junia,

00:17:56.380 --> 00:17:59.046
and he says,
"These are esteemed among

00:17:59.046 --> 00:18:00.380
the Apostles."
 

00:18:00.380 --> 00:18:03.733
"Among the Apostles,"
that sounds like he's actually

00:18:03.733 --> 00:18:06.980
saying that Andronicus and Junia
are themselves Apostles.

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:09.877
And Paul thinks himself--the
Apostles, in Paul's view,

00:18:09.877 --> 00:18:12.118
doesn't include just the
twelve, right?

00:18:12.118 --> 00:18:14.772
Because he thinks he's an
Apostle and he's not one of the

00:18:14.772 --> 00:18:15.200
twelve.
 

00:18:15.200 --> 00:18:18.934
The word "Apostle"
for Paul is wider than the

00:18:18.934 --> 00:18:22.808
twelve, and it refers to people
who go out and spread the

00:18:22.808 --> 00:18:23.568
Gospel.
 

00:18:23.568 --> 00:18:27.656
Apparently, Paul is calling two
people, Andronicus and Junia,

00:18:27.656 --> 00:18:30.108
"Apostles"
in Romans 16.

00:18:30.108 --> 00:18:32.491
Interestingly enough,
that word "Junia,"

00:18:32.491 --> 00:18:35.068
that might be in your
translation as "Junia"

00:18:35.068 --> 00:18:37.574
nowadays,
but in older English versions,

00:18:37.574 --> 00:18:39.944
it was translated as
"Junias,"

00:18:39.944 --> 00:18:41.828
which would be a man's name.
 

00:18:41.828 --> 00:18:43.656
In Latin, if you add an
"s"

00:18:43.656 --> 00:18:45.838
on that word it looks like a
man's name,

00:18:45.838 --> 00:18:47.048
if you don't have the
"s,"

00:18:47.048 --> 00:18:48.118
it looks like a woman's name.
 

00:18:48.118 --> 00:18:51.220
There was debate among scholars
about how to translate it.

00:18:51.220 --> 00:18:54.244
It looks the same basically in
Greek because of the way the

00:18:54.244 --> 00:18:55.808
word occurs in the sentence.
 

00:18:55.808 --> 00:18:57.946
When you translated it,
are you going to make it a

00:18:57.946 --> 00:18:59.298
man's name or a woman's name?
 

00:18:59.298 --> 00:19:01.846
People had always made it a
man's name.

00:19:01.846 --> 00:19:02.250
Why?
 

00:19:02.250 --> 00:19:04.289
Because scholars just
thought--of course all these

00:19:04.289 --> 00:19:06.704
scholars are men themselves
throughout hundreds of years of

00:19:06.704 --> 00:19:07.810
tradition--
they thought,

00:19:07.810 --> 00:19:09.220
well you can't have a woman
Apostle,

00:19:09.220 --> 00:19:11.338
so it must be a man's name.
 

00:19:11.338 --> 00:19:15.086
In the seventies some feminist
biblical scholars came along and

00:19:15.086 --> 00:19:17.143
pointed out that
"Junias"

00:19:17.143 --> 00:19:20.163
is a very,
very, very rare man's name but

00:19:20.163 --> 00:19:23.690
"Junia"
is a very common woman's name,

00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:26.815
and argued again through
textual criticism that Paul

00:19:26.815 --> 00:19:29.450
originally was addressing a
woman, Junia.

00:19:29.450 --> 00:19:32.617
And now you have basically most
scholars admitting that this is

00:19:32.617 --> 00:19:33.130
a woman.
 

00:19:33.130 --> 00:19:34.108
It's a woman's name.
 

00:19:34.108 --> 00:19:36.692
Paul was addressing a man,
Andronicus, and a woman,

00:19:36.692 --> 00:19:38.759
Junia, and calling them both
Apostles.

00:19:38.759 --> 00:19:42.778
There's some evidence that Paul
actually doesn't have such a

00:19:42.778 --> 00:19:46.660
negative view of women if he's
going to allow them to have

00:19:46.660 --> 00:19:49.180
leadership roles in his
churches.

00:19:49.180 --> 00:19:52.450
So you've got Paul in rather
confusing situations.

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:54.098
Is Paul a feminist?
 

00:19:54.098 --> 00:20:00.990
Is he for egalitarian theology
with men and women?

00:20:00.990 --> 00:20:03.633
How does this relate to these
different issues that come up in

00:20:03.633 --> 00:20:04.240
his letters?
 

00:20:04.240 --> 00:20:09.224
Those are Paul's basic views of
both marriage and the family,

00:20:09.224 --> 00:20:12.048
and sex, and the roles of
women.

00:20:12.048 --> 00:20:15.175
Often in early Christianity,
in the history of Christianity,

00:20:15.175 --> 00:20:16.818
these two things go together.
 

00:20:16.818 --> 00:20:20.221
What a text is going to teach
about the role of women in the

00:20:20.221 --> 00:20:23.738
church and in the world often
has something to do with what it

00:20:23.738 --> 00:20:25.410
teaches about the family.
 

00:20:25.410 --> 00:20:29.778
Most of the time when a text is
really, really pro-family,

00:20:29.778 --> 00:20:33.920
they teach the subordination of
women more directly.

00:20:33.920 --> 00:20:38.656
When they're anti-family,
they often tend to allow women

00:20:38.656 --> 00:20:41.930
bigger roles in their
congregations.

00:20:41.930 --> 00:20:43.970
So it's kind of a pairing that
goes along,

00:20:43.970 --> 00:20:46.944
and that's exactly what we'll
see this week when we see the

00:20:46.944 --> 00:20:50.125
