You didn't know you were going
to learn Greek,

00:24:37.038 --> 00:24:40.494
and you're getting some good
cocktail party information,

00:24:40.494 --> 00:24:42.568
and even some Greek language.
 

00:24:42.568 --> 00:24:45.401
Gnosis is the word for
knowledge here,

00:24:45.401 --> 00:24:48.748
and this guy is attacking
people who are going around

00:24:48.748 --> 00:24:51.578
boasting about falsely called
knowledge.

00:24:51.578 --> 00:24:55.224
Again, that's led some scholars
to say is he talking about some

00:24:55.224 --> 00:24:56.460
kind of Gnosticism?
 

00:24:56.460 --> 00:24:58.430
Is that what he's opposing?
 

00:24:58.430 --> 00:25:01.251
That would go along with this
idea that they're using this

00:25:01.251 --> 00:25:03.480
word gnosis in ways he
doesn't like.

00:25:03.480 --> 00:25:06.548
They're teaching myths,
they're teaching asceticism,

00:25:06.548 --> 00:25:08.519
they're teaching the avoidance
of marriage,

00:25:08.519 --> 00:25:11.640
well that does look a bit like
other early Christian,

00:25:11.640 --> 00:25:14.367
second century Christian
groups, some of whom their

00:25:14.367 --> 00:25:17.426
opponents would call Gnostics,
but we don't have enough

00:25:17.426 --> 00:25:19.470
information for it to be easy to
tell.

00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:28.028
Now look at one more text,
this is II Timothy 2:18,

00:25:28.028 --> 00:25:38.298
he's actually giving some names
of people he doesn't like.

00:25:38.298 --> 00:25:40.858
In 2:18 it says,
"These people have swerved

00:25:40.858 --> 00:25:44.071
from the truth by claiming that
the resurrection has already

00:25:44.071 --> 00:25:45.269
taken place."
 

00:25:45.269 --> 00:25:47.210
He's condemning that.
 

00:25:47.210 --> 00:25:50.332
Remember how I even talked
about with Colossians and

00:25:50.332 --> 00:25:53.538
Ephesians last time,
you had this idea that they

00:25:53.538 --> 00:25:56.940
almost sound like the
resurrection has already taken

00:25:56.940 --> 00:25:57.538
place.
 

00:25:57.538 --> 00:26:00.118
In your baptism with Christ you
have been raised with Christ,

00:26:00.118 --> 00:26:02.897
and maybe there are other
people wandering around the

00:26:02.897 --> 00:26:05.178
second century,
Christians, saying that you've

00:26:05.178 --> 00:26:06.759
already been raised from the
dead,

00:26:06.759 --> 00:26:07.930
you've already experienced the
resurrection.

00:26:07.930 --> 00:26:09.670
This author really condemns
that.

00:26:09.670 --> 00:26:11.632
He wants to say,
no, the resurrection hasn't

00:26:11.632 --> 00:26:14.138
taken place yet,
so he's condemning false

00:26:14.138 --> 00:26:17.487
teachers for all kinds of
different activities and

00:26:17.487 --> 00:26:19.808
teachings that he doesn't like.
 

00:26:19.808 --> 00:26:22.834
So we're seeing a definite
split here between different

00:26:22.834 --> 00:26:24.009
kinds of Paulinism.
 

00:26:24.009 --> 00:26:27.872
There's a Paulinism represented
by these texts which is

00:26:27.872 --> 00:26:31.019
pro-family, pro-marriage,
pro-procreation.

00:26:31.019 --> 00:26:33.715
We'll talk about later that
he's for having children and

00:26:33.715 --> 00:26:36.354
mentions this explicitly;
anti-asceticism,

00:26:36.354 --> 00:26:40.957
against forcing people to
control what they eat and these

00:26:40.957 --> 00:26:45.806
sorts of things and this idea
about maybe Jewish myths being

00:26:45.806 --> 00:26:50.078
something and the teaching of
the resurrection.

00:26:50.078 --> 00:26:54.443
I Timothy 1:9,
then, gets us into another

00:26:54.443 --> 00:27:01.210
issue: what is the law and what
is this author's take on it?

00:27:01.210 --> 00:27:05.635
I Timothy 1:9,8:
"Now we know that the law

00:27:05.635 --> 00:27:09.868
is good if one uses it
legitimately."

00:27:09.868 --> 00:27:12.111
That of course can be a
quotation right out of Romans

00:27:12.111 --> 00:27:14.440
because Romans itself has Paul
says the law is good.

00:27:14.440 --> 00:27:17.920
This means understanding that
the law is laid down not for the

00:27:17.920 --> 00:27:20.660
innocent but for the lawless and
disobedient,

00:27:20.660 --> 00:27:23.519
for the godless and sinful,
for the unholy and profane,

00:27:23.519 --> 00:27:25.200
for those who kill their father
or mother,

00:27:25.200 --> 00:27:26.442
or murderers,
fornicators,

00:27:26.442 --> 00:27:27.698
sodomite,
slave traders,

00:27:27.698 --> 00:27:29.815
liars, perjurers,
whatever else is contrary to

00:27:29.815 --> 00:27:32.118
sound teaching that contradicts
the gracious,

00:27:32.118 --> 00:27:34.049
the glorious gospel of the
blessed God,

00:27:34.049 --> 00:27:35.519
which he entrusted to me.
 

00:27:35.519 --> 00:27:38.993
Notice this guy doesn't have
really a problem with the law

00:27:38.993 --> 00:27:41.858
that we've seen sometimes in
Paul's writings.

00:27:41.858 --> 00:27:46.239
The law is basically just a set
of rules designed to keep people

00:27:46.239 --> 00:27:48.950
who can't control themselves in
line.

00:27:48.950 --> 00:27:52.118
In fact, he goes on to say that
if you're a good person you

00:27:52.118 --> 00:27:54.358
don't even need to worry about
the law.

00:27:54.358 --> 00:27:58.038
Now this is again different
from what Paul's view is.

00:27:58.038 --> 00:28:01.768
Paul did not want his Gentile
followers to keep the Jewish

00:28:01.768 --> 00:28:05.170
law, and Paul said in Romans
that the law is good.

00:28:05.170 --> 00:28:10.104
For Paul the law is still this
cosmic entity almost that

00:28:10.104 --> 00:28:11.720
invaded history.
 

00:28:11.720 --> 00:28:14.570
This is very much Galatians,
remember when I gave the

00:28:14.570 --> 00:28:17.862
lecture on Galatians and Romans
I talked about how the Jewish

00:28:17.862 --> 00:28:20.440
law for Paul is not simply a
list of rules.

00:28:20.440 --> 00:28:24.490
It was this thing that came
into the cosmos as an invader,

00:28:24.490 --> 00:28:27.809
it enslaved humanity,
it was the pedagogue that

00:28:27.809 --> 00:28:31.708
swatted humanity down when
humanity was in its childish

00:28:31.708 --> 00:28:32.430
state.
 

00:28:32.430 --> 00:28:36.788
Obeying the law for Paul is
equal to trying to worship the

00:28:36.788 --> 00:28:41.375
stoichea of the cosmos,
these elemental spirits of the

00:28:41.375 --> 00:28:42.368
universe.
 

00:28:42.368 --> 00:28:45.920
So the law for Paul isn't
simply a list of rules.

00:28:45.920 --> 00:28:50.150
The law for Paul is a very
ambiguous cosmic entity.

00:28:50.150 --> 00:28:53.298
It's just mythological in a
sense for Paul.

00:28:53.298 --> 00:28:56.019
For this author that's not what
the law is.

00:28:56.019 --> 00:28:58.430
The law--you don't need to obey
it,

00:28:58.430 --> 00:29:02.076
he says, and he's against
teaching his Gentile converts to

00:29:02.076 --> 00:29:04.481
keep the Jewish law,
but he just says,

00:29:04.481 --> 00:29:05.578
it's not important.
 

00:29:05.578 --> 00:29:07.980
It's only for people who are
sinners who can't control

00:29:07.980 --> 00:29:08.568
themselves.
 

00:29:08.568 --> 00:29:11.160
As long as you're not a sinner,
as long as you don't do this

00:29:11.160 --> 00:29:13.794
list of things that I can give
you, you don't need to concern

00:29:13.794 --> 00:29:14.980
yourself about the law.
 

00:29:14.980 --> 00:29:18.681
So this is another one of the
reasons that people like me say,

00:29:18.681 --> 00:29:20.318
this is not Paul writing.
 

00:29:20.318 --> 00:29:23.788
People who believe Paul wrote
these letters would say,

00:29:23.788 --> 00:29:26.208
well they're written years
later, it's to a different

00:29:26.208 --> 00:29:28.180
context,
and Paul changed his mind,

00:29:28.180 --> 00:29:31.382
or Paul's nuancing his message
differently for a different

00:29:31.382 --> 00:29:32.000
context.
 

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:34.221
So there are scholars who would
defend these letters being by

00:29:34.221 --> 00:29:35.630
Paul and that's what they would
say.

00:29:35.630 --> 00:29:39.078
I look at it and I say that's
so not like Paul.

00:29:39.078 --> 00:29:42.933
It's a totally different view
of the law and its role in the

00:29:42.933 --> 00:29:45.940
cosmos than you see in Romans or
Galatians,

00:29:45.940 --> 00:29:49.728
which is another piece of
evidence for me that Paul is not

00:29:49.728 --> 00:29:51.588
the author of this letter.
 

00:29:51.588 --> 00:29:55.288
The strategy,
then, of this author,

00:29:55.288 --> 00:29:58.488
he's trying to argue against
all kinds of myths and practices

00:29:58.488 --> 00:30:01.740
that somebody's going through
Paul's churches and teaching.

00:30:01.740 --> 00:30:05.605
So he writes a letter in Paul's
name, seemingly addressed to

00:30:05.605 --> 00:30:09.209
Paul's follower Timothy,
and he lays out what he doesn't

00:30:09.209 --> 00:30:10.519
like about that.
 

00:30:10.519 --> 00:30:12.150
But that's not all of his
strategy.

00:30:12.150 --> 00:30:15.626
What is his strategy for
combating these things that he

00:30:15.626 --> 00:30:17.430
considers false teachings?
 

00:30:17.430 --> 00:30:21.509
First, he makes the church
itself a household.

00:30:21.509 --> 00:30:24.215
Now this is where all that
lecturing in the first part of

00:30:24.215 --> 00:30:26.355
the semester,
when I talked over and over

00:30:26.355 --> 00:30:28.528
again, what is the patriarchal
household,

00:30:28.528 --> 00:30:29.723
what is the Roman household,
what is the

00:30:29.723 --> 00:30:31.573
paterfamilias,
what is the structure of the

00:30:31.573 --> 00:30:33.261
household,
what is the patron client

00:30:33.261 --> 00:30:35.525
relationship,
what is the role of wives and

00:30:35.525 --> 00:30:38.000
women in the household,
and children, and slaves?

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:41.007
All of that was because when
you get to some of these aspects

00:30:41.007 --> 00:30:44.229
of early Christianity,
this author is using the Roman

00:30:44.229 --> 00:30:47.250
household as the model for the
church itself.

00:30:47.250 --> 00:30:50.048
That wasn't the way Paul did
it, right?

00:30:50.048 --> 00:30:53.489
Paul never talked about the
church as if it just had the

00:30:53.489 --> 00:30:55.490
same structure of a household.
 

00:30:55.490 --> 00:30:59.067
He didn't talk about men always
being on top of the leadership

00:30:59.067 --> 00:31:01.590
organization,
and he didn't promote marriage

00:31:01.590 --> 00:31:04.289
very much, which is what this
author does.

00:31:04.289 --> 00:31:12.173
I Timothy 3:14:
I hope to come to you soon,

00:31:12.173 --> 00:31:16.563
but I am writing these
instructions to you so that if I

00:31:16.563 --> 00:31:21.682
am delayed you may know how one
ought to behave in the household

00:31:21.682 --> 00:31:23.700
of God,
which is the church of the

00:31:23.700 --> 00:31:25.573
living God,
the pillar and bulwark of the

00:31:25.573 --> 00:31:25.910
truth.
 

00:31:25.910 --> 00:31:29.269
The church is the household of
God.

00:31:29.269 --> 00:31:32.467
The same thing happens in I
Timothy 5, the beginning of I

00:31:32.467 --> 00:31:34.833
Timothy 5:
Do not speak harshly to an

00:31:34.833 --> 00:31:36.801
older man;
speak to him as a father,

00:31:36.801 --> 00:31:39.520
to younger men as brothers,
to older women as mothers,

00:31:39.520 --> 00:31:42.240
to younger women as sisters,
with absolute purity.

00:31:42.240 --> 00:31:45.150
Notice everybody in the church
has some familial role.

00:31:45.150 --> 00:31:48.487
Older guys are fathers,
your younger men in the church

00:31:48.487 --> 00:31:51.173
are your brothers,
younger women sisters,

00:31:51.173 --> 00:31:54.266
older women mothers,
everybody has a household role

00:31:54.266 --> 00:31:55.130
in the church.
 

00:31:55.130 --> 00:31:58.220
This is different--we might
think this is automatic but,

00:31:58.220 --> 00:32:00.523
notice, this is not treating
the church as an

00:32:00.523 --> 00:32:02.608
ecclesia,
that Greek word that we

00:32:02.608 --> 00:32:04.028
translate "church."
 

00:32:04.028 --> 00:32:06.430
Where did the term
ecclesia come from?

00:32:06.430 --> 00:32:07.500
Do you remember?
 

00:32:07.500 --> 00:32:10.585
In Greek, what does the term
ecclesia originally refer

00:32:10.585 --> 00:32:11.819
to in classical Greek?
 

00:32:11.819 --> 00:32:12.960
Student:  Assembly.
 

00:32:12.960 --> 00:32:14.720
Prof: The assembly of
the city.

00:32:14.720 --> 00:32:17.611
It's the assembly of the
city-state that came together

00:32:17.611 --> 00:32:19.630
for political purposes and to
vote.

00:32:19.630 --> 00:32:23.367
It comes out of the Greek
democracy, with its notions of

00:32:23.367 --> 00:32:27.241
some kind of equality among
citizens and all the--at least

00:32:27.241 --> 00:32:29.690
the men citizens getting a vote.
 

00:32:29.690 --> 00:32:33.301
It's important that early
Christians, for some reason,

00:32:33.301 --> 00:32:36.982
chose this word ecclesia
to describe their house

00:32:36.982 --> 00:32:37.869
churches.
 

00:32:37.869 --> 00:32:39.690
It was ridiculous.
 

00:32:39.690 --> 00:32:41.457
An outsider would have--might
have thought this is kind of

00:32:41.457 --> 00:32:43.259
ridiculous;
you're using the term that

00:32:43.259 --> 00:32:46.490
people would have heard as the
town assembly for a few people

00:32:46.490 --> 00:32:48.430
who can fit into one dining
room?

00:32:48.430 --> 00:32:53.886
It's kind of acceding more
importance to yourself than you

00:32:53.886 --> 00:32:55.420
really should.
 

00:32:55.420 --> 00:32:58.289
I think it's important that
early Christian groups use that

00:32:58.289 --> 00:32:59.380
term for themselves.
 

00:32:59.380 --> 00:33:00.983
Why didn't early Christian
groups call themselves

00:33:00.983 --> 00:33:01.818
"synagogues"?
 

00:33:01.818 --> 00:33:04.900
That was a term already in use
by Jews;

00:33:04.900 --> 00:33:06.848
it would have been a normal
term to use.

00:33:06.848 --> 00:33:09.201
We don't find many early
Christians using the term

00:33:09.201 --> 00:33:11.170
"synagogue"
for their groups.

00:33:11.170 --> 00:33:13.550
We do find them using
ecclesia very quickly,

00:33:13.550 --> 00:33:15.598
but an ecclesia isn't a
household.

00:33:15.598 --> 00:33:19.430
What this author is doing is
shifting,

00:33:19.430 --> 00:33:22.809
in a not so subtle way,
understanding these house

00:33:22.809 --> 00:33:25.980
groups as being more like town
assemblies,

00:33:25.980 --> 00:33:31.298
and making them look more like
Roman household.

00:33:31.298 --> 00:33:35.259
Also, then, men have certain
roles.

00:33:35.259 --> 00:33:39.144
I Timothy 2:8:
"I desire than that in

00:33:39.144 --> 00:33:43.957
every place the men should pray,
lifting up holy hands without

00:33:43.957 --> 00:33:46.986
anger or argument,
also that the women should pray

00:33:46.986 --> 00:33:49.950
lifting up holy hands without
argument."

00:33:49.950 --> 00:33:53.269
No, Dale's lying to you again.
 

00:33:53.269 --> 00:33:55.500
The women should dress
themselves modestly,

00:33:55.500 --> 00:33:57.170
decently, and in suitable
clothing,

00:33:57.170 --> 00:33:58.890
not with their hair braided
[girls,

00:33:58.890 --> 00:34:02.615
are you listening?]
or with gold,

00:34:02.615 --> 00:34:04.773
pearls,
or expensive clothes,

00:34:04.773 --> 00:34:07.285
but with good works as is
proper for women who profess

00:34:07.285 --> 00:34:08.280
reverence for God.
 

00:34:08.280 --> 00:34:12.170
Let a woman learn in silence
with full submission.

00:34:12.170 --> 00:34:15.739
I permit no woman to teach or
have authority over a man.

00:34:15.739 --> 00:34:17.289
She is to keep silent.
 

00:34:17.289 --> 00:34:19.992
For Adam was formed first,
then Eve, and Adam was not

00:34:19.992 --> 00:34:22.485
deceived but the woman was
deceived, and became a

00:34:22.485 --> 00:34:23.369
transgressor.
 

00:34:23.369 --> 00:34:25.693
Yet she will be saved through
childbearing,

00:34:25.693 --> 00:34:28.846
provided they continue in faith
and love and holiness with

00:34:28.846 --> 00:34:29.510
modesty.
 

00:34:29.510 --> 00:34:33.317
Now this is something that my
mom used to hate it when they

00:34:33.317 --> 00:34:35.679
would preach about this in
church.

00:34:35.679 --> 00:34:39.996
Also, it's controversial;
does it mean that she's saved

00:34:39.996 --> 00:34:42.989
from the dangers of
childbirth?

00:34:42.989 --> 00:34:43.949
That's one way of reading it.
 

00:34:43.949 --> 00:34:46.675
She'll be saved from the
dangers of childbirth if she

00:34:46.675 --> 00:34:48.250
lives a pious and holy life.
 

00:34:48.250 --> 00:34:50.940
Or, a bit more of a radical way
of reading,

00:34:50.940 --> 00:34:54.056
it would be to say,
by having babies women help

00:34:54.056 --> 00:34:58.382
constitute their own salvation--
that having children is one of

00:34:58.382 --> 00:35:00.880
the ways that women save
themselves.

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:05.500
Either way you look at it,
this author really wants women

00:35:05.500 --> 00:35:09.460
to be in a subordinate role,
silent in church.

00:35:09.460 --> 00:35:12.179
They can't have any leadership
authority or teaching authority

00:35:12.179 --> 00:35:12.760
over a man.
 

00:35:12.760 --> 00:35:15.119
As we'll see,
they do have some offices.

00:35:15.119 --> 00:35:18.353
There are roles that women can
play in the Pastoral Epistles,

00:35:18.353 --> 00:35:20.079
but not in authority over men.
 

00:35:20.079 --> 00:35:23.239
Then there's this odd thing
about childbearing.

00:35:23.239 --> 00:35:28.409
And I think what it means is
that childbearing actually can

00:35:28.409 --> 00:35:32.510
help save women from their sins
in some way.

00:35:32.510 --> 00:35:35.945
Women have to be modestly
dressed, no jewelry,

00:35:35.945 --> 00:35:38.159
saved through childbearing.
 

00:35:38.159 --> 00:35:41.945
In order to maintain this kind
of household structure,

00:35:41.945 --> 00:35:46.161
a very hierarchical household
structure, this author sets up

00:35:46.161 --> 00:35:48.018
offices in the church.
 

00:35:48.018 --> 00:35:50.295
And here's another reason to
call these "the Pastoral

00:35:50.295 --> 00:35:51.811
Epistles,"
because he's setting up

00:35:51.811 --> 00:35:52.650
pastoral offices.
 

00:35:52.650 --> 00:35:55.460
Look in I Timothy 3:1-7,
"The saying is sure

00:35:55.460 --> 00:35:58.800
whoever is aspires to the office
of bishop desires a noble

00:35:58.800 --> 00:35:59.679
task."
 

00:35:59.679 --> 00:36:02.644
Now a bishop--does anybody have
a different translation for what

00:36:02.644 --> 00:36:04.340
I just read as
"bishop"?

00:36:04.340 --> 00:36:05.170
Student: 
"Overseer."

00:36:05.170 --> 00:36:06.413
Prof:
"Overseer,"

00:36:06.413 --> 00:36:08.110
yes, "overseer"
is a translation.

00:36:08.110 --> 00:36:11.170
Anybody have a different
translation?

00:36:11.170 --> 00:36:13.650
The word "bishop"
here is--

00:36:13.650 --> 00:36:16.268
the Greek word is
episkopos,

00:36:16.268 --> 00:36:18.869
where we get the English word
"bishop"

00:36:18.869 --> 00:36:22.130
and you get the name for the
Episcopal church because it's a

00:36:22.130 --> 00:36:23.679
church that has bishops.
 

00:36:23.679 --> 00:36:27.373
In Greek it basically means
"an overseer"

00:36:27.373 --> 00:36:29.960
or "someone in
charge."

00:36:29.960 --> 00:36:31.730
The bishop must be above
reproach,

00:36:31.730 --> 00:36:33.070
married only once,
temperate, sensible,

00:36:33.070 --> 00:36:34.869
respectable,
hospitable, an apt teacher,

00:36:34.869 --> 00:36:36.760
not a drunkard,
not violent but gentle,

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:38.550
not quarrelsome,
not a lover of money.

00:36:38.550 --> 00:36:40.324
He must manage his own
household well,

00:36:40.324 --> 00:36:43.300
keeping his children submissive
and respectful in every way.

00:36:43.300 --> 00:36:45.590
For if someone does not know
how to manage his own household,

00:36:45.590 --> 00:36:47.079
how can he take care of God's
church?

00:36:47.079 --> 00:36:49.210
Again the church is a household.
 

00:36:49.210 --> 00:36:52.860
If you're going to be the
bishop over the church you have

00:36:52.860 --> 00:36:55.605
to be married,
because how can you manage the

00:36:55.605 --> 00:36:58.929
household of the church if you
can't prove it by managing your

00:36:58.929 --> 00:37:00.130
own household well?
 

00:37:00.130 --> 00:37:02.981
"He must not be a recent
convert"

00:37:02.981 --> 00:37:05.490
The bishop or the
episkopos is already

00:37:05.490 --> 00:37:07.829
himself now a male head of
household.

00:37:07.829 --> 00:37:12.949
The other office he talks about
in 5:17,

00:37:12.949 --> 00:37:17.021
"Let the elders,"
now just as the word we

00:37:17.021 --> 00:37:21.340
translated "bishop"
or "overseer,"

00:37:21.340 --> 00:37:25.250
comes from the Greek word
episkopos,

00:37:30.949 --> 00:37:33.599
the Greek for elder here is
presbyteros,

00:37:33.599 --> 00:37:36.585
presbyter, and this is where
the Presbyterian church gets the

00:37:36.585 --> 00:37:37.630
name of its church.
 

00:37:37.630 --> 00:37:40.592
They're Presbyterians because
the Presbyterian church rejected

00:37:40.592 --> 00:37:43.409
the use of bishops like they
found in Catholic and Anglican

00:37:43.409 --> 00:37:45.291
churches,
and chose a plurality of

00:37:45.291 --> 00:37:47.445
elders, so they're called
"elders"

00:37:47.445 --> 00:37:50.327
in the Presbyterian church,
and the Presbyterian church

00:37:50.327 --> 00:37:52.885
comes from this Greek word
meaning "elder,"

00:37:52.885 --> 00:37:55.050
presbyteros and this is
actually--

00:37:55.050 --> 00:37:58.795
this came to be later in
English the name for a bishop

00:37:58.795 --> 00:38:03.317
who was not just the head of one
particular church but became the

00:38:03.317 --> 00:38:06.842
head of a series of churches,
a bunch of churches,

00:38:06.842 --> 00:38:10.157
that is the bishop now is not
the head of one church but the

00:38:10.157 --> 00:38:14.030
head of a whole diocese,
that is a geographical grouping.

00:38:14.030 --> 00:38:16.159
The word's changed a bit but
that's--

00:38:16.159 --> 00:38:19.925
bishop comes from this word and
presbyteros turned into

00:38:19.925 --> 00:38:22.516
the word priest,
so one of the suggested

00:38:22.516 --> 00:38:25.967
etymology's for where the
English word "priest"

00:38:25.967 --> 00:38:28.739
came from is from this Greek
word itself,

00:38:28.739 --> 00:38:35.081
and you can kind of say
presbyteros,

00:38:35.081 --> 00:38:36.440
priest.
 

00:38:36.440 --> 00:38:41.726
It just kind of happens in
English over a few hundred

00:38:41.726 --> 00:38:42.539
years.
 

00:38:42.539 --> 00:38:46.795
Elders also have to have wives,
be family men,

00:38:46.795 --> 00:38:49.539
and all this sort of thing.
 

00:38:49.539 --> 00:38:51.902
There are other offices to look
at--real quickly we're going to

00:38:51.902 --> 00:38:52.590
go through this.
 

00:38:52.590 --> 00:38:56.869
Deacons: 3:8:
Deacons likewise must be

00:38:56.869 --> 00:38:59.529
serious, not double-tongued,
not indulging in much wine,

00:38:59.529 --> 00:39:00.690
not greedy for money.
 

00:39:00.690 --> 00:39:02.773
They must hold fast to the
mystery of the faith with a

00:39:02.773 --> 00:39:03.518
clear conscience.
 

00:39:03.518 --> 00:39:05.601
Let them first be tested,
then, if they prove themselves

00:39:05.601 --> 00:39:07.079
blameless, let them serve as
deacons.

00:39:07.079 --> 00:39:09.170
Women likewise must be serious.
 

00:39:09.170 --> 00:39:11.500
Now there's an exegetical
problem, does this

00:39:11.500 --> 00:39:13.722
"women"
refer to women who would

00:39:13.722 --> 00:39:15.889
themselves independently be
deacons?

00:39:15.889 --> 00:39:18.132
In other words,
is he allowing women to be

00:39:18.132 --> 00:39:20.867
deacons on their own,
or is it supposed to be taken

00:39:20.867 --> 00:39:23.329
to be just the wives of the male
deacons?

00:39:23.329 --> 00:39:25.449
That they're called deacons
also, or deaconesses;

00:39:25.449 --> 00:39:28.324
the word for "deacon"
here comes from the Greek

00:39:28.324 --> 00:39:29.300
diakonos,
 

00:39:37.599 --> 00:39:40.969
it comes into English directly,
and that word just means

00:39:40.969 --> 00:39:43.974
"a servant,"
"someone who serves or

00:39:43.974 --> 00:39:45.199
ministers."
 

00:39:45.199 --> 00:39:48.788
The women in 3:11--some
exegetes would say this shows

00:39:48.788 --> 00:39:52.929
that this author does allow at
least women to be deacons,

00:39:52.929 --> 00:39:55.172
deaconesses,
and they have certain kinds of

00:39:55.172 --> 00:39:55.599
roles.
 

00:39:55.599 --> 00:39:59.599
Verse 12: "Let deacons be
married only once,

00:39:59.599 --> 00:40:01.969
let them manage their children
and their households well,

00:40:01.969 --> 00:40:04.313
for those who serve well as
deacons gain a good standing for

00:40:04.313 --> 00:40:05.070
themselves."
 

00:40:05.070 --> 00:40:09.250
Notice, in the beginning,
all of these roles,

00:40:09.250 --> 00:40:12.530
whether it's the elder,
presbyter, or the bishop--

00:40:12.530 --> 00:40:15.623
and there's some debate about
whether "presbyter"

00:40:15.623 --> 00:40:18.610
refers to the same role as a
bishop in these letters--

00:40:18.610 --> 00:40:21.541
they seem to be combined in
some of the later pastoral

00:40:21.541 --> 00:40:23.407
letters,
or whether they refer to two

00:40:23.407 --> 00:40:25.929
separate offices,
so there's a bit of a debate.

00:40:25.929 --> 00:40:29.027
All of these people,
whether you're from bishops,

00:40:29.027 --> 00:40:32.061
presbyters, deacons,
they all are required to be

00:40:32.061 --> 00:40:35.289
married and all are required to
have children.

00:40:35.289 --> 00:40:38.237
In the beginning of early
Christianity,

00:40:38.237 --> 00:40:41.730
see, you did not have the
celibate ministr.

00:40:41.730 --> 00:40:43.880
The celibate ministry comes
about later.

00:40:43.880 --> 00:40:48.306
This is in line with this
author's intention to set up the

00:40:48.306 --> 00:40:51.956
church as a household structure
with men on top,

00:40:51.956 --> 00:40:54.518
women having their own roles.
 

00:40:54.518 --> 00:41:02.432
Now there are other roles here
too, look at I Timothy 5:3-10,

00:41:02.432 --> 00:41:09.159
"Honor widows,"
this is I Timothy 5:3:

00:41:09.159 --> 00:41:11.840
Honor widows who are really
widows.

00:41:11.840 --> 00:41:14.519
If a widow has children or
grandchildren they should first

00:41:14.519 --> 00:41:17.295
learn their religious duty to
their own family and make some

00:41:17.295 --> 00:41:20.168
repayment to their parents,
for this is pleasing in God's

00:41:20.168 --> 00:41:20.500
sight.
 

00:41:20.500 --> 00:41:23.012
The real widow,
left alone, has set her hope on

00:41:23.012 --> 00:41:25.525
God and continues in
supplications and prayers,

00:41:25.525 --> 00:41:26.510
night and day.
 

00:41:26.510 --> 00:41:29.576
But the widow who lives for
pleasure is dead even while she

00:41:29.576 --> 00:41:30.000
lives.
 

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.280
Give these commands as well so
that they may be above reproach.

00:41:33.280 --> 00:41:35.759
Whoever does not provide for
relatives, and especially for

00:41:35.759 --> 00:41:37.586
family members,
has denied the faith and is

00:41:37.586 --> 00:41:39.110
worse than an unbeliever."
 

00:41:39.110 --> 00:41:41.233
[Now it gets really
interesting.]

00:41:41.233 --> 00:41:44.949
Let a widow be put on the list,
let her be registered.

00:41:44.949 --> 00:41:50.119
It seems like he's actually
creating another kind of office

00:41:50.119 --> 00:41:54.309
in the church,
that is, the office of widows.

00:41:54.309 --> 00:41:56.333
And, sure enough,
in Christianity later,

00:41:56.333 --> 00:41:58.826
"widow"
became almost like an office in

00:41:58.826 --> 00:42:00.018
early Christianity.
 

00:42:00.018 --> 00:42:03.099
They could be registered,
and they received financial

00:42:03.099 --> 00:42:04.579
help from the churches.
 

00:42:04.579 --> 00:42:08.269
"Let a widow be put on the
list if she is not less than

00:42:08.269 --> 00:42:11.710
sixty years old and has been
married only once."

00:42:11.710 --> 00:42:14.768
Notice over and over here,
we've seen this thing about

00:42:14.768 --> 00:42:15.980
being married once.
 

00:42:15.980 --> 00:42:18.983
Apparently this author believes
in marriage and wants people to

00:42:18.983 --> 00:42:21.744
be married, but his ideal is
that people should be married

00:42:21.744 --> 00:42:22.179
once.
 

00:42:22.179 --> 00:42:25.610
You certainly should not be
divorced and remarried.

00:42:25.610 --> 00:42:29.943
Paul himself forbids people in
his church from being divorced

00:42:29.943 --> 00:42:33.340
and remarried,
as we saw in I Corinthians 11.

00:42:33.340 --> 00:42:36.780
But this author seems to say
that if you're married and your

00:42:36.780 --> 00:42:40.047
spouse dies, he still kind of
prefers that these women be

00:42:40.047 --> 00:42:41.039
married once.
 

00:42:41.039 --> 00:42:44.327
He also said that the bishop or
the presbyteros should be

00:42:44.327 --> 00:42:47.652
men who are married only once,
so multiple marriages are

00:42:47.652 --> 00:42:51.117
really frowned on even though
marriage itself is highly

00:42:51.117 --> 00:42:51.760
valued.
 

00:42:51.760 --> 00:42:55.507
This led to what is currently
the practice in many of the

00:42:55.507 --> 00:42:56.780
eastern churches.
 

00:42:56.780 --> 00:42:58.500
Eastern Orthodox,
the Greek Orthodox,

00:42:58.500 --> 00:43:00.804
the Russian Orthodox,
they do not forbid their

00:43:00.804 --> 00:43:03.706
priests from being married,
but you have to be married

00:43:03.706 --> 00:43:05.179
before you become a priest.
 

00:43:05.179 --> 00:43:08.496
So you'll have a lot of young
men in Greece or Russia who are

00:43:08.496 --> 00:43:11.369
going to become priests,
and they want to quickly get

00:43:11.369 --> 00:43:13.250
married right out of seminary.
 

00:43:13.250 --> 00:43:16.378
So they're looking around for a
partner, because if they become

00:43:16.378 --> 00:43:19.610
ordained as a priest and they're
not married, they're expected to

00:43:19.610 --> 00:43:20.570
stay unmarried.
 

00:43:20.570 --> 00:43:23.726
If their wife dies after they
become a priest,

00:43:23.726 --> 00:43:27.655
they're expected to stay
celibate and single for the rest

00:43:27.655 --> 00:43:29.340
of their lives also.
 

00:43:29.340 --> 00:43:32.610
This led to the tradition in
Eastern Christianity,

00:43:32.610 --> 00:43:35.175
that you can be a married
priest, unlike the Roman

00:43:35.175 --> 00:43:37.563
Catholic Church,
but only if you get married

00:43:37.563 --> 00:43:39.010
before you become a priest.
 

00:43:39.010 --> 00:43:43.389
And it kept this idea of being
married once only.

00:43:43.389 --> 00:43:48.184
I can't go into the rest of
this but notice how this whole

00:43:48.184 --> 00:43:51.969
hierarchy of man and woman in a
household,

00:43:51.969 --> 00:43:54.474
old and young,
is also extended to children

00:43:54.474 --> 00:43:55.250
and slaves.
 

00:43:55.250 --> 00:44:00.182
Already in Colossians and
Ephesians we had what we called

00:44:00.182 --> 00:44:04.940
the household codes:
masters treat your slaves well;

00:44:04.940 --> 00:44:06.199
slaves be obedient to your
masters;

00:44:06.199 --> 00:44:10.280
husbands treat your wives well;
wives submit to your husbands;

00:44:10.280 --> 00:44:13.139
children submit to your fathers;
fathers treat your

00:44:13.139 --> 00:44:14.949
children--these are called
household codes.

00:44:14.949 --> 00:44:17.731
Already in Colossians and
Ephesians they set up the

00:44:17.731 --> 00:44:20.179
household in a clear
hierarchical patriarchal

00:44:20.179 --> 00:44:20.960
situation.
 

00:44:20.960 --> 00:44:23.849
That is intensified in the
Pastoral Epistles.

00:44:23.849 --> 00:44:26.817
You have much longer household
codes, and, whereas in

00:44:26.817 --> 00:44:29.784
Colossians and Ephesians
that--those writers at least

00:44:29.784 --> 00:44:31.840
said there was some reciprocity.
 

00:44:31.840 --> 00:44:34.438
They would address the slaves,
you would have to obey the

00:44:34.438 --> 00:44:36.896
master but they would also
address the master and say,

00:44:36.896 --> 00:44:38.150
treat your slaves well.
 

00:44:38.150 --> 00:44:41.467
When you get to the Pastoral
Epistles they left out the

00:44:41.467 --> 00:44:43.545
reciprocity,
it's mainly directed to the

00:44:43.545 --> 00:44:45.045
slaves,
to the children,

00:44:45.045 --> 00:44:46.650
to the wives,
saying,

00:44:46.650 --> 00:44:47.820
submit.
 

00:44:47.820 --> 00:44:52.831
This is the strategy that this
writer uses to combat the forms

00:44:52.831 --> 00:44:56.119
of Christianity that he doesn't
like,

00:44:56.119 --> 00:45:00.851
to construct the church as a
rigid patriarchal household in

00:45:00.851 --> 00:45:03.380
which each person has a role.
 

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:05.956
Even young women,
he says they're not supposed to

00:45:05.956 --> 00:45:08.996
be enrolled as widows,
if you have young women who are

00:45:08.996 --> 00:45:10.418
widows,
and they start running around

00:45:10.418 --> 00:45:11.829
gossiping and getting in a lot
of trouble,

00:45:11.829 --> 00:45:14.170
he says get them married off
again.

00:45:14.170 --> 00:45:17.510
Old women, of course,
you couldn't marry off again,

00:45:17.510 --> 00:45:19.378
they're not enough old men
around in the ancient world to

00:45:19.378 --> 00:45:22.548
marry them off,
so he creates this structure by

00:45:22.548 --> 00:45:24.407
which women,
older women,

00:45:24.407 --> 00:45:27.257
get pulled back into the
household by this role as

00:45:27.257 --> 00:45:27.840
widows.
 

00:45:27.840 --> 00:45:31.900
No matter what happens to a
woman, in this author's view,

00:45:31.900 --> 00:45:34.885
they have to be put back into
their submissive place in the

00:45:34.885 --> 00:45:37.429
household structure,
even if that means creating a

00:45:37.429 --> 00:45:39.539
new role for them called
"widows."

00:45:39.539 --> 00:45:45.090
This strategy this author uses
to bring Paul into his own time.

00:45:45.090 --> 00:45:48.405
He's taking a Paul that we've
seen as a bit different from

00:45:48.405 --> 00:45:51.898
this and he's reinventing Paul
for a second century Christian

00:45:51.898 --> 00:45:55.389
environment and restructuring
the church as a household.

00:45:55.389 --> 00:45:59.072
We'll see an author on
Wednesday doing precisely the

00:45:59.072 --> 00:46:00.590
opposite with Paul.
 

00:46:00.590 --> 00:46:02.050
See you next time.
 

